defaultThis consultation response has been prepared on behalf of Sheffield City Region (SCR) Executive and South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive (SYPTE). The response reflects the evolving governance in SCR towards a Combined Authority and the wider conte
defaultxt of the Strategic Economic Plan (SEP), which Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP) areas are currently preparing for Government.
default* What is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level decision-making on transport expenditure? defaultWhat are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?defaultThe rationale for devolution is about 
defaultputting decision making closer to the people affected
default.  
defaultEngland has become one of the most centralised countries in Europ
defaulte, therefore increasing the disconnect between Whitehall and ‘the people’
default.  
defaultWhitehall faces the significant challenge of understanding why investment in transport, or any other type of infrastructure, is needed. 
defaultThis 
defaultneed is best understood by those who a
defaultre directly accountable to the people where the investment is needed.
defaultThis new approach allows City Regions to make long term, strategic plans 
defaulton major infrastructure and avoid the stop-go delivery of national projects.  
defaultIn SCR, the BRT North scheme incurr
defaulted an 8 month delay and resulted in additional funding being sought as a consequence of additional processes introduced by Government. The addition of the development pool and the Best and Final Bidding Process increased the level of uncertainty for the Pr
defaultoject, which could have been avoided through greater local controls. 
default, 
default 
defaultDevolvement of decisions on transport expenditure is only the start of the journey. Areas like the Sheffield City Region (SCR) are 
defaultstrengthening
default governance arrangements and 
defaultestablishing 
defaultan accountable body to deal with strategic transport and economic rege
defaultneration decision making. In the SCR this is in the form of a Combined Authority. The wider remit of these bodies
default and the role of the private sector
default, 
defaultare 
defaultcritical to ensuring that investment 
defaultdecisions 
defaultsolve the economic problem, not just transport problem.
default 
defaultAt present 
defaultthe Combined Authority
default 
defaultis 
defaultlacking two important features, which 
defaultif available, 
defaultwould 
defaultfurther enhance 
defaultthe delivery of 
defaultthis wider remit of strategic economic regeneration. 
defaultCurrently, 
defaultthe Combined Authority
default 
defaultis 
defaultunable to claim VAT and can only lev
defaulty for transport funding.  
defaultIt is vital that Combined Authorities can raise funds to spend on investment across a range of activities including transport, and that the statute that underpins the Combined Authority
default,
default enables this function.
